<?xml version="1.0" encoding="UTF-8"?>

<section xml:id="sec-chapter-6-problems">
  <title>Chapter 6 Review Problems</title>
  
  <example>
    <title>Volume of Revolution</title>
    
    <statement>
      <p>
        Consider the region above <m>y=x^2</m> and below <m>y=7x</m>, graphed below. The axes are intentionally left blank, so you may need to use algebra to determine information about where the graphs intersect.
      </p>
      <image source="CurvesForRotation.PNG" width="50%">
        <shortdescription>A coordinate plane displaying the line y = 7x and the parabola y = x squared. Both curves pass through the origin. The line increases at a constant rate, while the parabola curves upward more slowly at first and then becomes steeper, eventually intersecting the line again to the right.</shortdescription>
      </image>
      <p>
        <ol>
          <li>
            <p>
              Assuming you will be finding a volume of revolution for this region rotated around the <m>x</m>-axis, <em>draw a typical slice on the picture above</em>.
            </p>
          </li>
          <li>
            <p>
              Set up, but do not evaluate, the definite integral that gives the volume of this region when it is rotated around the <m>x</m>-axis.
            </p>
          </li>
          <li>
            <p>
              Describe in a few sentences how the definite integral that you gave in part 2 represents the volume of revolution. You do not need to describe anything about the bounds of integration. You may receive some credit for indicating how you plugged expressions into a formula you had memorized, but in order to receive full credit, you must justify your answer using geometry. You may draw additional pictures as part of your description.
            </p>
          </li>
        </ol>
      </p>
    </statement>

    <solution>
      <p>
        <ol>
          <li>
            <image source="CurvesForRotationSolution.PNG" width="50%">
              <shortdescription>A coordinate plane displaying the line y = 7x and the parabola y = x squared. Both curves pass through the origin. The line increases at a constant rate, while the parabola curves upward more slowly at first and then becomes steeper, eventually intersecting the line again to the right. A narrow vertical red rectangle between the two curves is highlighted (with the top of the rectangle touching the y = 7x curve and the bottom of the rectangle touching the y = x squared curve) and is labeled "a slice," indicating a representative vertical slice between the graphs.</shortdescription>
            </image>
          </li>
          <li>
            <p>
              First, find the intersctions:
                <md>
                  <mrow> x^2 \amp = 7x</mrow>
                  <mrow> x^2 - 7x \amp = 0</mrow>
                  <mrow> x (x-7) \amp = 0</mrow>
                  <mrow> x = 0 \quad \amp \text{or} \quad x = 7</mrow>
                </md>
              Use these points of intersection to set up the definite integral. All of the following forms are equivalent and would be correct solutions:
                <md>
                  <mrow> \amp \int_0^7 ( \pi(7x)^2 - \pi(x^2)^2 ) \; dx</mrow>
                  <mrow> \amp \int_0^7 \pi ( (7x)^2 - (x^2)^2 ) \; dx</mrow>
                  <mrow> \amp \int_0^7 \pi ( 49x^2 - x^4 ) \; dx</mrow>
                </md>
            </p>
          </li>
          <li>
            <p>
              Upon rotating a slice (from part 1) around the <m>x</m>-axis, the trace is a washer-like shape. The area of the full washer (without the hole) is <m>\pi(\text{radius})^2</m>. In this case, <m>\text{radius}=7x</m>, so <m>\pi(7x)^2</m>. Similarly, the area of the hole is <m>\pi(x^2)^2</m>. Subtracting the area of the hole from the area of the full washer gives the area of the washer slice -- the correct integrand.
            </p>
            <image source="WasherRotated.PNG" width="50%">
              <shortdescription>A three-dimensional drawing of a washer-shaped solid formed by rotating a vertical slice around the x-axis. The washer has a circular outer edge and a smaller circular hole in the center. A horizontal blue line through the center represents the x-axis of rotation. A narrow red rectangular strip on the front face of the washer is labeled "slice from (a)," indicating the original vertical slice that was revolved to create the washer.</shortdescription>
            </image>
          </li>
        </ol>
      </p>
    </solution>

  </example>

  <example>
    <title>Area in Polar Coordinates</title>
    
    <statement>
      <p>
        A student wishes to find the area in the first quadrant between the first and second "spirals" of the <em>Archimedean spiral</em>, a curve whose graph is given by the equation <m>r=\theta</m>. The region of interest is shaded in the picture below.
      </p>
      <image source="ArchimedeanSpiral.PNG" width="50%">
        <shortdescription>A coordinate plane showing an Archimedean spiral in blue (labeled r = theta), starting at the origin and winding outward counterclockwise. The spiral passes through multiple rotations around the origin. In the first quadrant, the region between two successive turns of the spiral is shaded with many thin radial line segments extending outward from the origin to the outer curve, forming a fan-like filled area between the inner and outer portions of the spiral.</shortdescription>
      </image>
      <p>
        The student determines that the answer is zero, as reasoned below, but they feel like they have made a mistake. Identify the student's mistake and give an expression involving definite integrals (<em>which you do not need to evaluate</em>) that would correctly represent the area of the shaded region.
      </p>
      <p>
        <em>Student Reasoning</em>
        <ol>
          <li>
            <p>
              We will use the formula <m>\displaystyle\int_a^b \left(\frac{(f(\theta)^2)}{2}-\frac{(g(\theta))^2}{2}\right)\;d\theta</m>, where <m>r=f(\theta)</m> describes the "larger" curve (further from the origin) and <m>r=g(\theta)</m> describes the curve closer to the origin. In both cases, <m>f(\theta)=g(\theta)=\theta</m>, the Archimedean spiral.
            </p>
          </li>
          <li>
            <p>
              The bounds of integration are the angles that encompass the first quadrant, corresopnding to <m>a=0</m> radians and <m>b=\frac{\pi}{2}</m> radians.
            </p>
          </li>
          <li>
            <p>
              Plugging this all in, we have
              <md>
                <mrow> \int_a^b \left( \frac{(f(\theta)^2)}{2} - \frac{(g(\theta))^2}{2} \right) \; d\theta \amp = \int_0^{\pi/2} \left( \frac{\theta^2}{2} - \frac{\theta^2}{2} \right) \; d\theta</mrow>
                <mrow> \amp = \int_0^{\pi/2} 0 \; d\theta</mrow>
                <mrow> \amp = 0</mrow>
              </md>
            </p>
          </li>
        </ol>
      </p>
    </statement>

    <solution>
      <p>
        The mistake is subtle, but the student cannot use the same formula for both <m>f(\theta)</m> and <m>g(\theta)</m> because they do not correspond to the same range of <m>\theta</m> values. The portion of the curve further from the origin, <m>f(\theta)</m>, has made a full <m>2\pi</m> rotation already and therefore corresponds to <m>\theta</m> values ranging from <m>2\pi</m> to <m>\frac{5\pi}{2}</m>.
      </p>
      <p>
        One option to fix this would be to correctly represent the area between the curves as the area "under" the larger curve minus the area "under" the smaller curve:
        <me>\int_{2\pi}^{5\pi/2} \frac{\theta^2}{2} \; d\theta - \int_0^{\pi/2} \frac{\theta^2}{2} \; d\theta</me>
      </p>
      <p>
        An alternative solution would be to note that the "larger" curve, <m>f(\theta)</m>, corresponds to <m>\theta</m> values that are <m>2\pi</m> larger than the <m>\theta</m> values on the "smaller" curve <m>g(\theta)</m>, so the answer could be given by the following single definite integral:
        <me>\int_0^{\pi/2} \left( \frac{(\theta+2\pi)^2}{2} - \frac{\theta^2}{2} \right) \; d\theta</me>
      </p>
    </solution>

  </example>

  <example>
    <title>Work Pumping Water, Version A</title>
    
    <statement>
      <p>
        The work required to pump water out of a tank is given by the following integral:
          <me>W = \int_a^b A(h)\, D(h)\, \delta(h)\, dh</me>
        which is defined by the following <em>four important components</em>:
        <ul>
          <li>
            <m>a</m> and <m>b</m> are constant values representing the appropriate bounds of integration,
          </li>
          <li>
            <m>A(h)</m> is a function that gives the area of a slice,
          </li>
          <li>
            <m>D(h)</m> is a function that gives the distance a slice must be lifted, and
          </li>
          <li>
            <m>\delta(h)</m> is a function that gives the density of the fluid (in weight per unit volume) within a slice.
          </li>
        </ul>
      </p>
      <p>
        <ol>
          <li>
            <p>
              Determine values or formulas for the <em>four important components</em> exactly for the following specific problem:
            </p>
            <p>
              <em>Problem:</em> A rectangular tank is oriented upright. The height of the tank is <m>13</m> ft, and the length and width of the tank are <m>2</m> ft by <m>9</m> ft. The tank is full of water (which has a constant weight density of <m>62.4</m> pounds per cubic foot), and the water is to be pumped out of the top of the tank.
            </p>
            <p>
              To receive full credit, you must draw a picture with a typical slice and clearly label what distance is represented by <m>h</m>, since there are multiple valid ways of setting up the problem. <em>You only need to define the components; you do not need to evaluate the integral itself.</em>
            </p>
          </li>
          <li>
            <p>
              The sub-parts below are unrelated. For each scenario described below, justify in complete sentences which of the <em>four important components</em> would be affected in the new context. Describe all components affected; there may be more than one.
            <ul>
              <li>
                <p>
                  One of the length/width dimensions of the tank is made smaller.
                </p>
              </li>
              <li>
                <p>
                  Only the top few feet of water are to be pumped out of the tank.
                </p>
              </li>
            </ul>
            </p>
          </li>
        </ol>
      </p>
    </statement>

    <solution>
      <p>
        <ol>
          <li>
            <image source="RectangularTank1a.PNG" width="50%">
              <shortdescription>An illustration of a rectangular tank drawn in three dimensions. The tank is labeled 13 feet tall, 9 feet long (front edge), and 2 feet deep (side edge). A horizontal blue slice of water is shown partway up the tank, with the surface shaded light blue. An arrow labeled "slice" points to the thin horizontal layer of water, indicating a cross-sectional slice used for volume calculations. On the right side, a vertical red bracket labeled "h" indicates the depth of the water from the top of the tank to the slice.</shortdescription>
            </image>
            <p>
              Let <m>h</m> be the distance down from the top of the tank.
              <ul>
                <li><m>a=0</m>, <m>b=13</m></li>
                <li><m>A(h)=2\cdot9=18</m></li>
                <li><m>D(h)=h</m></li>
                <li><m>\delta(h)=62.4</m></li>
              </ul>
              The total work required is:
                <me>\int_0^{13} 18 (62.4) h \; dh</me>
            </p>
          </li>
          <li>
            <p>
              <ul>
                <li>
                  <p>
                    <m>A(h)</m> would change because the area <m>A(h)=\text{length}\times\text{width}</m>, so shrinking the length/width will shrink the area.
                  </p>
                </li>
                <li>
                  <image source="RectangularTank1b.PNG" width="50%">
                    <shortdescription>An illustration of a rectangular tank drawn in three dimensions. The tank is labeled 13 feet tall. A horizontal blue slice of water is shown partway up the tank, with the surface shaded light blue. An arrow labeled "slice" points to the thin horizontal layer of water, indicating a cross-sectional slice used for volume calculations. On the right side, a vertical red bracket labeled "h" indicates the depth of the water from the top of the tank to the slice. The top of the tank has a depth label of "a=0" and the bottom of the tank has a depth label of "b=13".</shortdescription>
                  </image>
                  <p>
                    In the setup above, <m>a</m> and <m>b</m> correspond to the values of <m>h</m> at the top and the bottom of the tank. Limiting to pumping the top few feet would change the value of <m>b</m> (making it smaller).
                  </p>
                </li>
              </ul>
            </p>
          </li>
        </ol>
      </p>
    </solution>

  </example>

  <example>
    <title>Work Pumping Water, Version B</title>
    
    <statement>
      <p>
        The work required to pump water out of a tank is given by the following integral:
          <me>W = \int_a^b A(h)\, D(h)\, \delta(h)\, dh</me>
        which is defined by the following <em>four important components</em>:
        <ul>
          <li>
            <m>a</m> and <m>b</m> are constant values representing the appropriate bounds of integration,
          </li>
          <li>
            <m>A(h)</m> is a function that gives the area of a slice,
          </li>
          <li>
            <m>D(h)</m> is a function that gives the distance a slice must be lifted, and
          </li>
          <li>
            <m>\delta(h)</m> is a function that gives the density of the fluid (in weight per unit volume) within a slice.
          </li>
        </ul>
      </p>
      <p>
        <ol>
          <li>
            <p>
              Determine values or formulas for the <em>four important components</em> exactly for the following specific problem:
            </p>
            <p>
              <em>Problem:</em> A cylindrical tank is oriented upright (so that its circular base is on the ground). The height of the tank is <m>12</m> ft and the radius is <m>4</m> ft. The tank is full of water (which has a constant weight density of <m>62.4</m> pounds per cubic foot), and the water is to be pumped out of the top of the tank.
            </p>
            <p>
              To receive full credit, you must draw a picture with a typical slice and clearly label what distance is represented by <m>h</m>, since there are multiple valid ways of setting up the problem. <em>You only need to define the components; you do not need to evaluate the integral itself.</em>
            </p>
          </li>
          <li>
            <p>
              The sub-parts below are unrelated. For each scenario described below, justify in complete sentences which of the <em>four important components</em> would be affected in the new context. Describe all components affected; there may be more than one.
            <ul>
              <li>
                <p>
                  The radius of the tank is made smaller.
                </p>
              </li>
              <li>
                <p>
                  The tank is instead filled with two or more fluids which have separated so the denser fluids are closer to the bottom of the tank.
                </p>
              </li>
            </ul>
            </p>
          </li>
        </ol>
      </p>
    </statement>

    <solution>
      <p>
        <ol>
          <li>
            <image source="CylindricalTank1.PNG" width="50%">
              <shortdescription>A vertical cylindrical tank drawn in three dimensions. The bottom circular base has a line drawn to represent the radius, labeled r = 4 ft. A horizontal red circle inside the cylinder marks a cross-sectional slice at height h above the bottom. A blue arrow on the left measures h upward from the base, labeled from h = 0 ft at the bottom (corresponding to a = 0) to h = 12 ft at the top (corresponding to b = 12). A red arrow on the right labeled D(h) indicates the depth from the slice up to the top of the tank.</shortdescription>
            </image>
            <p>
              Let <m>h</m> be the distance up from the bottom of the tank, as in the picture above.
              <ul>
                <li><m>a=0</m>, <m>b=12</m></li>
                <li><m>A(h)=\pi r^2=\pi\cdot4^2=16\pi \quad \text{(square feet)}</m></li>
                <li><m>D(h)=12-h \quad \text{(ft)}</m></li>
                <li><m>\delta(h)=62.4 \quad \text{(pounds per cubic foot)}</m></li>
              </ul>
              The total work required is:
                <me>\int_0^{12} (16\pi) (12-h) (62.4) \; dh</me>
            </p>
            <p>
              An alternative solution may be given where <m>h</m> is now the distance down from the top of the tank, as in the picture below.
            </p>
            <image source="CylindricalTank2.PNG" width="50%">
              <shortdescription>A vertical cylindrical tank drawn in three dimensions. The bottom circular base has a line drawn to represent the radius, labeled r = 4 ft. A horizontal red circle inside the cylinder marks a cross-sectional slice at a distance h below the top. A blue arrow on the left measures h downward from the top, labeled from h = 0 ft at the top (corresponding to a = 0) to h = 12 ft at the bottom (corresponding to b = 12). A red arrow on the right labeled D(h) indicates the depth from the slice up to the top of the tank.</shortdescription>
            </image>
            <p>
              <ul>
                <li><m>a=0</m>, <m>b=12</m></li>
                <li><m>A(h)=\pi r^2=\pi\cdot4^2=16\pi \quad \text{(square feet)}</m></li>
                <li><m>D(h)=h \quad \text{(ft)}</m></li>
                <li><m>\delta(h)=62.4 \quad \text{(pounds per cubic foot)}</m></li>
              </ul>
              In this case, the total work required would be given by:
                <me>\int_0^{12} (16\pi) (h) (62.4) \; dh</me>
            </p>
          </li>
          <li>
            <p>
              <ul>
                <li>
                  <p>
                    The radius of the tank shrinking means <em><m>A(h)</m> decreases</em>, since <m>A(h)=\pi r^2</m>. If the radius shrinks, so does <m>A(h)</m>. None of the other components are affected: <m>a</m>, <m>b</m>, and <m>D(h)</m> do not change since the water is still to be moved the same height, and <m>\delta(h)</m> is unchanged since the liquid is unchanged.
                  </p>
                </li>
                <li>
                  <p>
                    The fluids separating means only <m>\delta(h)</m> is affected, although <em>we do not have enough information to say how</em>. This is because the fluid density varies, and the density may now depend on where the slice is taken. Since the tank itself does not change, none of the other components are affected.
                  </p>
                </li>
              </ul>
            </p>
          </li>
        </ol>
      </p>
    </solution>

  </example>

</section>